  {
    "id": "UgwrjqzrrMpezPNsQfF4AaABAg",
    "author": "@awuk3468",
    "author_channel_id": "UCgX8I0YxvmpWWK27G8rMIag",
    "text": "Is the red as over exposed as it appears to be?  Perhaps some red plastic, like you get on sweet wrappers might help? You should use pixel strips and then you can change the colours of the LEDs individually, use an ESP or Arduino or something to control, that way you can also dim them and make some cool effects.",
    "likes": 1,
    "published_at": "2020-11-23T15:53:45Z",
    "reply_count": 2,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "UgwrjqzrrMpezPNsQfF4AaABAg.9GPb39b_-Vd9GRGnT2CZzm",
        "author": "@MyNameIsLukey",
        "author_channel_id": "UC7R08Y1PfEuBm63Sx_m-rZg",
        "text": "I think the red looks good to the naked eye, but the sweet wrapper idea is very cool.  I was going to connect a button and a potentiometer so I could turn it off and \"dim\" the light, but this specific sign only needs to be on when me or Rob is recording. That being said I might do an update video? Thanks mate! :)",
        "likes": 0,
        "published_at": "2020-11-24T07:26:27Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "UgwrjqzrrMpezPNsQfF4AaABAg.9GPb39b_-Vd9GRYKZbkuKf",
        "author": "@awuk3468",
        "author_channel_id": "UCgX8I0YxvmpWWK27G8rMIag",
        "text": "@MyNameIsLukey Perhaps a bit overkill for the sign you have made then, you could make another one, if you used pixel strips you could essentially do away with the stencil and use something like xLights to create the pattern, not sure how well it would look with colour bleed, but might be fun to experiment with, pixel strips are relatively cheap nowadays.  Just throwing some ideas out :)",
        "likes": 0,
        "published_at": "2020-11-24T09:59:39Z"
      }
    ]
  },
